        <hl1>Microsoft Breakup: A Serious Mistake</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Robert A McTamaney letter urges case against Microsoft be thrown out (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Stern Justice for Microsoft'' (editorial, June 8):</p>
        <p>Microsoft is one business, with lots of people sitting in rooms writing software, and writing consistently with all the others down the hall, not a group of disparate operations.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Stern Justice for Microsoft'' (editorial, June 8):</p>
        <p>Microsoft is one business, with lots of people sitting in rooms writing software, and writing consistently with all the others down the hall, not a group of disparate operations.</p>
        <p>It is very doubtful that Microsoft did anything wrong, given the wild success of all the supposed victims,  like Netscape. This whole case has been government gone berserk, and the more quickly it is thrown out, the better for the American consumer.</p>
        <p>ROBERT A. MCTAMANEY  New York, June 8, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is an antitrust lawyer.</p>
      </block>
